Visually it’s just as iconic as its predecessor; the Hipgnosis-designed cover with the eerie naked children continues to raise eyebrows, but there are some musical missteps as Zeppelin continues to shuffle through styles and genres. It’s good, in that they needed to retreat from the plodding aesthetic monotony of their first two, blues-based metal records, but still: "D'Yer Mak'er?” Zeppelin doing reggae was sort of ugly. However, most of the rest of it succeeds as Plant and Page continue to casually plunder their way through folk, rock, and whatever else comes to mind. Zoso or Led Zeppelin IV, a.k.a.
